[2] Distribution of reagents and antivirals (USA)
Date: Thu 30 Apr 2009
Source: Medscape Infectious Diseases [edited]
<http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/702187>


The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) is taking
ongoing steps against the influenza H1N1 virus, including deploying
the strategic national stockpile of antiviral drugs and making H1N1
testing kits available in all 50 states.

"We have completed deployment of antiviral stockpiles and other
materials for use in hospitals to 9 states," Richard Besser, MD,
acting director of the CDC, told reporters at a media briefing today
[30 Apr 2009]. "Materials are moving to the rest of the states, and
all of this should be completed by 3 May 2009," he said. "We are
deploying these supplies as a forward-leaning move in the event that
this becomes something much bigger than it already is," Dr. Besser said.

In addition, a total of 34 CDC staff have been sent out to 5
locations, including 11 people who have been sent to Mexico. A lab
has been set up in Mexico to conduct testing that will help confirm
cases of the virus.

To date, the CDC reports 109 confirmed cases of H1N1 influenza in the
United States in 11 affected states. The median age of infected
individuals is 16 years, with a range of 22 months to 81 years. A
total of 6 cases have been hospitalized, and there has been one
death, in Texas. "As we see more people infected, we will see a broad
spectrum of presentations, and I do expect that there will be more
deaths," Dr. Besser said. "We continue to be very aggressive in our
approach and will continue to do that until the situation tells us
that we no longer need to do so."

Until this week, testing for H1N1 could be done only at CDC.
Currently, New York and California have the ability to test for H1N1,
but reagent kits will go out to all states tomorrow, Dr. Besser said.

Plans to create a vaccine that will be effective against the strain
are underway. Currently, a seed strain is being grown so that it can
be distributed to manufacturers. The CDC is discussing a plan to
complete the production of next year's [2010] seasonal influenza
vaccine, and then they would switch over to manufacturing the H1N1
vaccine. "We still want to protect the country from seasonal flu and
to be able to protect from this new virus if we decide to do so," Dr.
Besser said. "Our hope is that we are able to see the transmission
now go away, with the efforts that are underway and what we know
about flu virus transmission, and be ready in the fall [2009] to
vaccinate people if we decide that is what is warranted," he added.
"That is the plan, to work towards developing a vaccine [to be ready]
in the fall."

Arnold S. Monto, MD, an influenza expert and professor of
epidemiology at the University of Michigan School of Public Health,
Ann Arbor, suggests that as with seasonal flu, all severe cases of
H1N1 influenza should be treated with antiviral drugs. "The problem
here is that we have issues of availability of the antivirals if we
have a large pandemic and/or a severe pandemic. The stockpiles will
only go so far. So all of us are going to have to pay attention to
national recommendations for antiviral use as they are developed.
More information on all of this will become available shortly.
According to Dr. Monto, antiviral drug manufacturers are increasing
production, but it may not be enough to meet excessive demand, so "we
must pay attention to which patients are experiencing the most severe
outcomes, and this may be different from seasonal flu, which mainly
affects the elderly."

--
