[4] On cross protection
Date: Mon 4 May 2009
From: Allen Kirchner <kirchn_a@bellsouth.net>


The question has been raised as to whether vaccination against the
seasonal flu -- the vaccine for which has for many years included
H1N1 -- would provide any protection against the emerging strain of H1N1.

I am traveling at this time and do not have access to my references,
but I think it was Sandbulte in 2007 [Cross-reactive neuraminidase
antibodies afford partial protection against H5N1 in mice and are
present in unexposed humans. Sandbulte MR, Jimenez GS, Boon AC, Smith
LR, Treanor JJ, Webby RJ. PLoS Med. 2007. - Mod.CP] who wrote about
the mitigating effects of the commonality of the neuraminidase
antigen. It was proposed that the common neuraminidase antigen, in
this case N1, would shorten the duration and lessen the severity of
infection of another subtype of influenza A with a different
hemagglutinin antigen but with the same neuraminidase. This was
proposed as one of the supporting arguments for universal seasonal
flu vaccination in the face of a possible pandemic of H5N1. It was
also suggested as an explanation of the relative non-lethality of the
1968 pandemic (H3N2) as compared to the 1957 pandemic (H2N2). In my
pandemic planning and preparedness classes, I have always used these
data as a supporting argument for universal seasonal influenza
vaccination. There has been nothing presented that suggests that this
is not a reasonable strategy.

I have read some reports from various public health officials that
suggested that seasonal flu vaccine would offer no protection against
the 2009 H1N1. I think that such advice is short-sighted, and
probably erroneous.

--
Allen W. Kirchner, M.D.
Senior Pandemic Clinical Consultant
CRA. Inc.
<kirchn_a@bellsouth.net>

[This is an important issue which needs to be addressed prior to
commitment to switch from production of seasonal vaccine to
production of a vaccine matched to provide protection against
infection by the new potentially pandemic 2009 H1N1 virus. - Mod.CP]

******
[5] In defense of surveillance
Date: Mon 4 May 2009
From: David Thomson <david.thomson@global.net.pg>


[A response to the critical article in the New York Times of 2 May
2009 [see: Influenza A (H1N1) - worldwide (05) 20090503.1657]
-----------------------------------------------
1. I believe that it would be unwarranted to suggest that the
surveillance systems that have been developed over recent years have,
in any way, been a failure because this virus has emerged and spread
beyond rapid containment to this stage. Emergence in a developing
country where there are a host of inter-current disease issues/events
at play will inevitably greatly complicate interpretation of data
that comes from surveillance; there are probably few diseases with
greater potential for rapid spread than flu, and emergence in
developing countries may well be the more expected situation.

The surveillance has put us on almost level terms with this disease
for the 1st time in history, and it probably won't be long before it
can put us ahead of the disease, where we really need to be, as long
as we get the support to stay the course.

2. I suspect that the coming non-flu season in the Northern
hemisphere may also present a unique opportunity. In the 1st
instance, it may not be valid to assume that this flu will follow the
seasonal pattern entirely; after all, it drew attention to itself in
Mexico because it was active at the very end or just out of the normal season.

On the other hand, however, a period of "reduced" epidemiological
activity should offer a unique opportunity to possibly get ahead of
the disease; the time to do that for highly infectious/transmissible
diseases like this is to hit them with everything whilst they are
down, because when they are up, they overwhelm. It usually requires
excellent surveillance to do that effectively because they are harder
to find, and surveillance data is harder to clearly interpret when
disease activity is low.

This, I believe, will probably be the acid test of the value of the
improved surveillance systems at global, regional and national levels.

3. This brings me my next point, if this disease is likely to be
overwhelming when it is up, it places a great deal more pressure on
keeping the disease out of or under good containment control in the
southern hemisphere, where the flu season is almost starting,
especially in temperate and sub-tropical regions.

4. I, therefore, sincerely hope that interest and support for
surveillance and control activities in the northern hemisphere do not
contract as the disease seasonally slows there (if it does that) and
likewise for the Southern hemisphere so that it does not rise to
become overwhelming there under the right seasonal conditions. If we
can keep it down in the south and it naturally wanes in the north,
enabling us to dig it out, then we may have a reasonable chance of
beating it back over the course of the coming year and thereby
possibly preventing emergence of worse in the not too distant future.
In my opinion, we must not lose sight of the good potential this
virus has for further reassortment, given the prevalence and types of
other flu viruses circulating in humans and animals at this juncture,
regardless of how "severe" this particular A(H1N1) strain may prove
to be in humans.

--
David Thomson
Sub-regional Animal Health Specialist
Secretariat of the Pacific Community
Port Moresby
Papua New Guinea
<david.thomson@global.net.pg>

